President Donald J. Trump and Prime Minister Shinzo Abe of Japan met in Washington D.C. for their first official meeting and expressed their commitment to strengthening the U.S.-Japan Alliance and economic relationship. They discussed the importance of maintaining the U.S.-Japan Alliance as the cornerstone of peace, prosperity, and freedom in the Asia-Pacific region. They also affirmed their commitment to defense cooperation, including the realignment of U.S. forces in Japan and the construction of the Futenma Replacement Facility. The leaders emphasized the importance of maintaining international order based on the rule of law and opposing any unilateral actions that undermine Japan's administration of the Senkaku Islands. They called for cooperation to safeguard the peace and stability of the East China Sea and the South China Sea, and urged North Korea to abandon its nuclear and ballistic missile programs. The leaders also discussed bilateral technological cooperation on defense innovation, as well as cooperation in the fields of space and cyberspace. In terms of economic relations, the leaders reaffirmed their commitment to strengthening economic relationships, promoting free and fair trade, and exploring a bilateral framework. They also expressed interest in cooperation across sectors that promote mutual economic benefits. President Trump accepted Prime Minister Abe's invitation for an official visit to Japan, and Vice President Pence's early visit to Tokyo was also welcomed.